		<div id="post_message_1373474">You guys are still playing this game?  I predicted this arbitrary nonsense earlier this month as a reason for why I quit.<br />
 <br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>Kaelon's Prediction</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != '') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = '';		this.innerText = ''; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none'; this.innerText = ''; this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
To me, the real issue isn't communication. It's arbitrary decisions being made by developers who don't really understand the strategic implication of those decisions across the entire game spectrum. Usually, these are inexperienced game developers who are making action-and-reaction based &quot;tactical&quot; decisions, with insufficient scope. Case in point: look at the Demonologist nerf, un-nerf, and re-nerf that happened within the first <b>two weeks</b> of gameplay. Many other classes report the same thing happening to them. <br />
<br />
I don't care if developers don't really communicate. I do care that developers make decent games and stick to their vision to improve the game and do so intelligently. This is why the original EverQuest was so well done despite the fact that Verant/SOE had a horrible track record of communication, it's why polished games from Blizzard endure for years, even decades, despite the fact that Blizzard by and large isn't really open to feedback from the public; and, it's why EverQuest 2 radically improved: because its new design leadership came in with a vision and they stuck by it.<br />
<br />
I'm beginning to believe that Conan designers don't really have a unified vision, given how haphazardly they are making these spontaneous decisions that seem to be radically depreciating the value of their game. Cancelling Conan was easy, since I was on the fence already. However, I cannot really imagine what it would be like for someone who actually loves this game to go through weeks and months of seeing it nerfed, un-nerfed, and re-nerfed back into oblivion before they are finally disenchanted and bitterly disillusioned enough to walk away from it. Utter torture. 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
 <br />
I will go a positive step further and suggest that they need to take the EQ2 route and fire their Design Lead, and bring in a visionary &quot;Producer&quot; (like Gallenite) to take control of design and development.  I think with the right hands, AoC can be an amazing game.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		
